294// Unique ID for every error
295// CAUTION: New enum values should be appended to the list only. Inserting
296// new enum values into the middle of the list results in changing the numeric
297// values of some ID's from one SDK release to the next. This in-turn breaks
298// PIX and customer tools/filters.
299typedef enum D3D12_MESSAGE_ID {
300 D3D12_MESSAGE_ID_UNKNOWN = 0,
301

1540//=============================================================================
1541// ID3D12InfoQueue
1542//
1543// Logs D3D12 Messages.
1544// This interface can be queried from ID3D12Device, as long as the device
1545// was created with the debug layer.
1546//
1547//
1548cpp_quote("#define D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_DEFAULT_MESSAGE_COUNT_LIMIT 1024")
1549[uuid(0742a90b-c387-483f-b946-30a7e4e61458), object, local, pointer_default(unique)]
1550interface ID3D12InfoQueue
1551 : IUnknown
1552{
1553 //=========================================================================
1554 // Methods for configuring how much data is stored in the queue.
1555
1556 // SetMessageCountLimit()
1557 // This sets how many messages are stored. When the queue is full,
1558 // new messages coming in push old messages out.
1559 // Passing -1 to SetMessageCountLimit means the queue has
1560 // unlimited size (go until out of memory or ClearStoredMessages()).
1561 // The default message count size is
1562 // D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_DEFAULT_MESSAGE_COUNT_LIMIT
1563 // Returns S_OK or E_INVALIDARG.
1564 HRESULT SetMessageCountLimit([annotation("_In_")] UINT64 MessageCountLimit);
1565
1566 // ClearStoredMessages
1567 void ClearStoredMessages();
1568
1569 //=========================================================================
1570 // Methods for retrieving data or statistics from the queue.
1571
1572 // GetMessage()
1573 // Retrieves messages, one at a time, from the queue which pass any
1574 // retrieval filter currently defined. If there is no retrieval filter,
1575 // all messages can be retrieved.
1576 // The MessageIndex parameter is a 0 based index into the results passing
1577 // the filter. The number of results is returned by
1578 // GetNumStoredMessagesAllowedByRetrievalFilter().
1579 //
1580 // Note this does not remove the message from the queue.
1581 //
1582 // pMessageByteLength inputs the size of the buffer passed in via
1583 // pMessage, and outputs the size of the message. pMessage can be NULL
1584 // when the size of the required buffer is being queried (return S_FALSE).
1585 //
1586 // NOTE: The returned buffer pMessage is NOT just the size of D3D12_MESSAGE,
1587 // it includes extra memory after the D3D12_MESSAGE for storing the string
1588 // description, which is pointed to from within D3D12_MESSAGE. Therefore
1589 // applications should check the size needed for pMessage as described above.
1590 //
1591 // Watch out for thread safety when making consecutive calls first to
1592 // determine the buffer size required and then to pass in the buffer and
1593 // retrieve the message, and also between calling
1594 // GetNumStoredMessagesAllowedByRetrievalFilter() and enumerating through
1595 // the results via GetMessagE().
1596 //
1597 // Returns: S_OK, S_FALSE, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY.
1598 HRESULT GetMessage(
1599 [annotation("_In_")] UINT64 MessageIndex,
1600 [annotation("_Out_writes_bytes_opt_(*pMessageByteLength)")] D3D12_MESSAGE* pMessage,
1601 [annotation("_Inout_")] SIZE_T* pMessageByteLength);
1602
1603 // GetNumMessagesAllowedByStorageFilter()
1604 // Returns how many messages sent to the queue passed
1605 // whatever storage filter was active upon receipt of
1606 // the message.
1607 // This can be a larger value than the message count limit,
1608 // returned by GetMessageCountLimit(), since old messages are discarded
1609 // when the queue is full to prevent overflow.
1610 UINT64 GetNumMessagesAllowedByStorageFilter();
1611
1612 // GetNumMessagesDeniedByStorageFilter()
1613 UINT64 GetNumMessagesDeniedByStorageFilter();
1614
1615 // GetNumStoredMessages()
1616 // Returns how many messages are currently stored in the queue.
1617 UINT64 GetNumStoredMessages();
1618
1619 // GetNumStoredMessagesAllowedByRetrievalFilter()
1620 // Returns how many messages that are currently in the queue
1621 // pass any retrieval filter that is currently set.
1622 // The MessageIndex parameter to GetMessage() indexes
1623 // an array of this many results.
1624 UINT64 GetNumStoredMessagesAllowedByRetrievalFilter();
1625
1626 // GetNumMessagesDiscardedByMessageCountLimit()
1627 UINT64 GetNumMessagesDiscardedByMessageCountLimit();
1628
1629 // GetMessageCountLimit
1630 // This is how many messages can be stored in the queue.
1631 // When the queue is full, new messages coming in push old messages out.
1632 // -1 means there is no limit.
1633 UINT64 GetMessageCountLimit();
1634
1635 //=========================================================================
1636 // Methods for filtering what gets stored in the queue
1637
1638 // AddStorageFilterEntries()
1639 // Adds to the existing entries at top of stack
1640 // Returns: S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY.
1641 HRESULT AddStorageFilterEntries(
1642 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter);
1643
1644 // GetStorageFilter()
1645 // Gets all entries at top of stack.
1646 // The application must allocate the output buffer. The size required can be
1647 // queried by passing null for pFilter and looking at the returned
1648 // pFilterByteLength (HRESULT is S_FALSE). Note that D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER contains
1649 // pointers - these will point to locations within the same
1650 // contiguous buffer - *pFilterByteLength is the total storage needed for all
1651 // data. So the application needs to only allocate/free the memory for pFilter.
1652 // Returns S_OK, S_FALSE, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1653 HRESULT GetStorageFilter(
1654 [annotation("_Out_writes_bytes_opt_(*pFilterByteLength)")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter,
1655 [annotation("_Inout_")] SIZE_T* pFilterByteLength);
1656
1657 // ClearStorageFilter()
1658 // Clears filter at the top of the stack (if there is one)
1659 void ClearStorageFilter();
1660
1661 // PushEmptyStorageFilter()
1662 // Push an empty storage filter on the stack to allow local filtering changes.
1663 // For convenience, this is automatically called by SetStorageFilter()
1664 // if the stack is empty. Thus if the stack is not needed, filters can be
1665 // defined without ever bothering to push or pop.
1666 // Returns S_OK or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1667 HRESULT PushEmptyStorageFilter();
1668
1669 // PushCopyOfStorageFilter()
1670 // Push a copy of the current filter so that local modifications can be made
1671 // starting from what currently exists.
1672 // Returns S_OK or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1673 HRESULT PushCopyOfStorageFilter();
1674
1675 // PushStorageFilter()
1676 // Push a filter passed as a parameter onto the stack. This is
1677 // just a helper for calling PushEmptyStorageFilter() followed
1678 // by AddStorageFilterEntries()
1679 // Returns S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY.
1680 HRESULT PushStorageFilter(
1681 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter);
1682
1683 // PopStorageFilter()
1684 // Pop the current storage filter off the stack (if there is one)
1685 void PopStorageFilter();
1686
1687 // GetStorageFilterStackSize()
1688 UINT GetStorageFilterStackSize();
1689
1690 //=========================================================================
1691 // Methods for filtering what gets read out of the queue by GetMessage().
1692
1693 // AddRetrievalFilterEntries()
1694 // Adds to the existing entries at top of stack
1695 // Returns: S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY.
1696 HRESULT AddRetrievalFilterEntries(
1697 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter);
1698
1699 // GetRetrievalFilter()
1700 // Gets all entries at top of stack.
1701 // The application must allocate the output buffer. The size required can be
1702 // queried by passing null for pFilter and looking at the returned
1703 // pFilterByteLength (HRESULT is S_FALSE). Note that D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER contains
1704 // pointers - these will point to locations within the same
1705 // contiguous buffer - *pFilterByteLength is the total storage needed for all
1706 // data. So the application needs to only allocate/free the memory for pFilter.
1707 // Returns S_OK, S_FALSE, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1708 HRESULT GetRetrievalFilter(
1709 [annotation("_Out_writes_bytes_opt_(*pFilterByteLength)")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter,
1710 [annotation("_Inout_")] SIZE_T* pFilterByteLength);
1711
1712 // ClearRetrievalFilter()
1713 // Clears filter at the top of the stack (if there is one)
1714 void ClearRetrievalFilter();
1715
1716 // PushEmptyRetrievalFilter()
1717 // Push an empty storage filter on the stack to allow local filtering changes.
1718 // For convenience, this is automatically called by SetRetrievalFilter()
1719 // if the stack is empty. Thus if the stack is not needed, filters can be
1720 // defined without ever bothering to push or pop.
1721 // Returns S_OK or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1722 HRESULT PushEmptyRetrievalFilter();
1723
1724 // PushCopyOfRetrievalFilter()
1725 // Push a copy of the current filter so that local modifications can be made
1726 // starting from what currently exists.
1727 // Returns S_OK or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1728 HRESULT PushCopyOfRetrievalFilter();
1729
1730 // PushRetrievalFilter()
1731 // Push a filter passed as a parameter onto the stack. This is
1732 // just a helper for calling PushEmptyRetrievalFilter() followed
1733 // by AddRetrievalFilterEntries()
1734 // Returns S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY.
1735 HRESULT PushRetrievalFilter(
1736 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_INFO_QUEUE_FILTER* pFilter);
1737
1738 // PopRetrievalFilter()
1739 // Pop the current storage filter off the stack (if there is one)
1740 void PopRetrievalFilter();
1741
1742 // GetRetrievalFilterStackSize()
1743 UINT GetRetrievalFilterStackSize();
1744
1745 //=========================================================================
1746 // Methods for adding entries to the queue.
1747
1748 // AddMessage()
1749 // This is used by D3D12 components to log messages. Nothing stops
1750 // applications from calling this, but it isn’t particularly useful.
1751 // If an application wishes to insert custom strings into the queue,
1752 // AddApplicationMessage() below is suggested. See below.
1753 //
1754 // Returns S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1755 HRESULT AddMessage(
1756 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_CATEGORY Category,
1757 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY Severity,
1758 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_ID ID,
1759 [annotation("_In_")] LPCSTR pDescription);
1760
1761 // AddApplicationMessage()
1762 // This is a convenience for applications that want
1763 // to insert strings of their own into the queue, perhaps to log issues
1764 // of its own, or to mark out points in time in the queue. This
1765 // has the same effect as calling AddMessage() above with the
1766 // following settings:
1767 // Category = D3D12_MESSAGE_CATEGORY_APPLICATION_DEFINED
1768 // Severity = <app selects from D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY>
1769 // ID = D3D12_MESSAGE_ID_STRING_FROM_APPLICATION
1770 // pDescription = <application provided string>
1771 //
1772 // Returns S_OK, E_INVALIDARG or E_OUTOFMEMORY
1773 HRESULT AddApplicationMessage(
1774 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY Severity,
1775 [annotation("_In_")] LPCSTR pDescription);
1776
1777 //=========================================================================
1778 // Methods for breaking on errors that pass the storage filter.
1779 HRESULT SetBreakOnCategory(
1780 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_CATEGORY Category,
1781 [annotation("_In_")] BOOL bEnable);
1782 HRESULT SetBreakOnSeverity(
1783 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY Severity,
1784 [annotation("_In_")] BOOL bEnable);
1785 HRESULT SetBreakOnID(
1786 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_ID ID,
1787 [annotation("_In_")] BOOL bEnable);
1788
1789 BOOL GetBreakOnCategory(
1790 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_CATEGORY Category);
1791 BOOL GetBreakOnSeverity(
1792 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY Severity);
1793 BOOL GetBreakOnID(
1794 [annotation("_In_")] D3D12_MESSAGE_ID ID);
1795
1796 //=========================================================================
1797 // Methods for globally muting debug spte from the InfoQueue
1798 void SetMuteDebugOutput(
1799 [annotation("_In_")] BOOL bMute);
1800 BOOL GetMuteDebugOutput();
1801};
1802
1803typedef enum D3D12_MESSAGE_CALLBACK_FLAGS
1804{
1805 D3D12_MESSAGE_CALLBACK_FLAG_NONE = 0x00,
1806 D3D12_MESSAGE_CALLBACK_IGNORE_FILTERS = 0x01,
1807
1808} D3D12_MESSAGE_CALLBACK_FLAGS;
1809
1810cpp_quote( "DEFINE_ENUM_FLAG_OPERATORS(D3D12_MESSAGE_CALLBACK_FLAGS)")
1811

1813 D3D12_MESSAGE_SEVERITY Severity,
1814 D3D12_MESSAGE_ID ID,
1815 LPCSTR pDescription,
1816 void* pContext);

1819interface ID3D12InfoQueue1

1830};
